🔷 ☕ Java 8 (2014) — Making Java Modern

🚩 Problem before Java 8

-Code was too long and repetitive
-Hard to process collections (lists, maps)
-Concurrency was complicated
-Frequent NullPointerException


🔑 What Java 8 introduced (with deeper meaning)

1. Lambda Expressions (Functional Programming)

Before:

Collections.sort(list, new Comparator<Integer>() {
    public int compare(Integer a, Integer b) {
        return a - b;
    }
});

After:

list.sort((a, b) -> a - b);

👉 Why important:

a.Reduced boilerplate
b.Introduced functional programming style
c.Enabled writing cleaner logic

2. Streams API (Data Processing Pipeline)

list.stream()
    .filter(x -> x > 10)
    .map(x -> x * 2)
    .toList();

👉 Think of it as:

A pipeline → filter → transform → collect

👉 Why important:

-Easy parallel processing
-Declarative style (WHAT, not HOW)

3. Functional Interfaces

Interfaces with one method

Example: Predicate, Function

👉 Needed to support lambdas

4. Optional (Null Safety)

Optional<String> name = Optional.ofNullable(getName());

👉 Why important:

(i)  Forces you to handle null properly
(ii) Reduces runtime crashes

5. New Date & Time API

LocalDate, LocalDateTime

👉 Fixed old issues like:

-Mutability
-Thread safety

✅ Final Impact

👉 Java 8 made Java:

(a)Cleaner
(b)Functional
(c)Easier to work with collections